Note:
JSON Parser - Builds JSON AST from tokens

This file implements a recursive descent parser for JSON. Takes tokens from
the JSON lexer and produces an Abstract Syntax Tree representing the
JSON structure.

Features:
- Recursive descent parsing
- Complete JSON grammar support (objects, arrays, primitives)
- Comprehensive error reporting with line/column information
- Memory-safe AST construction

JSON Grammar:
value    ::= object | array | string | number | "true" | "false" | "null"
object   ::= "{" members "}"
members  ::= pair ("," pair)*  | ε
pair     ::= string ":" value
array    ::= "[" elements "]"
elements ::= value ("," value)* | ε

Dependencies:
- json_lexer.runa (for tokenization)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/json/json_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: JSON AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant JSON_OBJECT as Integer is 1
Constant JSON_ARRAY as Integer is 2
Constant JSON_STRING as Integer is 3
Constant JSON_NUMBER as Integer is 4
Constant JSON_TRUE as Integer is 5
Constant JSON_FALSE as Integer is 6
Constant JSON_NULL as Integer is 7

Note: ============================================================================
Note: JSON AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A single discriminated record for all seven JSON node kinds. Combining
shape variants into one layout keeps the parser short and lets the
translator dispatch on `node_type` alone. The `is_integer` flag plus the
original `lexeme` is what lets json_to_hir round-trip floats without
losing precision: integers can be carried as a 64-bit value, but floats
preserve the exact source text for an authoritative HIR float literal.
The keys/children parallel-list arrangement for objects preserves source
order, which is observable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Nine 64-bit slots in declared order: node_type tag, value_string ptr,
value_int (integer value), is_integer flag (1 = use value_int, 0 = use
lexeme), lexeme (original number text), children list, keys list (parallel
to children for OBJECT), and line/column source position. Total size 72
bytes; offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40/48/56/64 are referenced directly by
create_json_node and every parse_* / translate_* call.
@End Implementation

Type called "JSONNode":
    node_type as Integer        Note: JSON node type constant
    value_string as Integer     Note: For STRING: pointer to string value
    value_int as Integer        Note: For NUMBER: integer value
    is_integer as Integer       Note: For NUMBER: 1 if integer, 0 if float
    lexeme as Integer           Note: For NUMBER: original token text (for float parsing)
    children as Integer         Note: For OBJECT/ARRAY: list of child nodes
    keys as Integer             Note: For OBJECT: list of keys (strings)
    line as Integer             Note: Source line number
    column as Integer           Note: Source column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
LL(1) recursive-descent parser state. Carrying `has_error` separately
from `error_message` lets the parser flag failure without paying the
allocate-and-copy cost when no message is set; an error can still be
detected even if message allocation OOM'd.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four 64-bit slots in declared order: lexer pointer (borrowed; caller
owns), current_token pointer (next token to consume), error_message
(owned heap string or 0), has_error boolean. Total size 32 bytes; offsets
0/8/16/24 are referenced directly by every parser Process.
@End Implementation

Type called "JSONParser":
    lexer as Integer            Note: JSON lexer instance
    current_token as Integer    Note: Current token
    error_message as Integer    Note: Error message (if any)
    has_error as Integer        Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructor that primes current_token with the first lexer output so the
parse_value entry point can dispatch immediately without a "have we read
any token yet" guard. Returning 0 on a null lexer is the same signal as
allocation failure -- callers handle both as "parser construction
failed".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guard lexer!=0. Allocate the 32-byte JSONParser block; on OOM return 0.
Write lexer at offset 0; zero current_token/error_message/has_error at
offsets 8/16/24. Call Lexer.next_token to read the first token and store
it at offset 8. Returns parser pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_json_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create JSON parser with lexer

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser_size be 32  Note: JSONParser: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize parser
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0  Note: current_token = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: has_error = false

    Note: Read first token
    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cleanup. The parser does NOT own the lexer (the caller created it and
freed it via destroy_json_lexer), and the current_token is the parser's
borrowed reference into lexer storage, so we only free the error_message
buffer here -- otherwise we'd double-free the lexer's resources.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If parser is 0, return 1. Read offset 16 (error_message); if non-zero,
deallocate. Then deallocate the parser block. Always returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_json_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy JSON parser and free resources

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Free error message if exists
    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Note: Note: Lexer is owned by caller, don't free it
    Note: Current token is freed by caller after parsing

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Token cursor advance. The previous token's lifetime is shared with the
lexer (the parser only borrows the pointer), so we never free it here;
fetching the next token via Lexer.next_token automatically retires the
old one. Returns the new token pointer for the (rare) caller that wants
to inspect it immediately.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read lexer at offset 0. Call Lexer.next_token to obtain the next token;
store it at offset 8 of parser. Return the new token pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let next_tok be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, next_tok

    Return next_tok
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming token predicate. Centralising the "null token" check (which
appears when the lexer has returned 0 for an out-of-range read) lets
every caller compare against a token type without re-implementing the
guard. parse_object and parse_array use it to peek for the empty-
collection case before committing to the iteration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read offset 8 (current_token) of parser. If 0, return 0. Otherwise read
offset 0 of the token (token_type) and compare; return 1 on match, 0
otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches expected type

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 0

    If token_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Match-or-error combinator. On a successful match the cursor advances;
on mismatch the caller-supplied error message is recorded and the
function returns 0. The grammar-level callers then propagate 0 back
through the recursion so the failing token's location is preserved in
the parser's state for diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Call check_token_type. On match (1), call advance_parser and return 1.
On mismatch (0), call set_parser_error with error_msg and return 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect token of given type, set error if not match

    Let is_match be proc check_token_type with parser, expected_type

    If is_match is equal to 1:
        proc advance_parser from parser
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Set error
    proc set_parser_error with parser, error_msg
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Replaces any prior error_message with a heap-owned NUL-terminated copy
of the supplied message and sets has_error=1. Owning the copy means the
caller can pass string literals without worrying about lifetime; the
parser releases the buffer on destroy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read offset 16 (error_message); if non-zero, deallocate. Compute
msg_length via StringCore.string_length, allocate msg_length+1 bytes,
memory_copy the message and NUL-terminate at offset msg_length. Store
the new buffer at offset 16 and 1 at offset 24 (has_error). Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_parser_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set parser error message

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    Note: Free previous error if exists
    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Note: Copy error message
    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let new_error be proc allocate from Layout with msg_length plus 1

    If new_error is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_error, 0, message, 0, msg_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with new_error, msg_length, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, new_error
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: has_error = true

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single factory for all seven JSONNode kinds. Zeroing every optional
slot at construction means individual parsers only need to populate the
slots their kind cares about, and the translator can safely test for
"has X?" by comparing against 0 without each parser remembering to zero
unused fields. Capturing line/column at construction binds the source
position to the node permanently so diagnostics produced after the
parser has advanced still report the right location.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 72 bytes (nine 64-bit fields); return 0 on OOM. Write
node_type at offset 0, zero offsets 8/16/24/32/40/48 (value_string,
value_int, is_integer, lexeme, children, keys), and write line/column
at offsets 56/64.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_json_node" takes node_type as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create JSON AST node

    Let node_size be 72  Note: JSONNode: 9 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize node
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: value_string = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: value_int = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: is_integer = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: lexeme = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: children = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: keys = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, column

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Recursive Descent Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The single value-position production in the JSON grammar:
  value ::= object | array | string | number | "true" | "false" | "null"
Every recursive descent (object members, array elements) eventually
reaches this dispatcher, so it's the natural place to materialise string
and number tokens into owned, NUL-terminated AST slots -- the source
buffer's lifetime is shorter than the AST's, so the parser cannot rely
on the lexer's interior pointers surviving downstream consumption.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read offset 8 (current_token); if 0, raise "Unexpected end of input".
Read token_type, line, column from token offsets 0/24/32. Dispatch:
  LBRACE              -> parse_object (recurse).
  LBRACKET            -> parse_array  (recurse).
  STRING              -> read lexeme/length at offsets 8/16, copy to a
                         heap-owned NUL-terminated buffer, populate node
                         at offset 8 (value_string), advance, return.
  NUMBER              -> read is_integer at offset 56, value_int at
                         offset 40, lexeme at 8, length at 16; create
                         the JSON_NUMBER node, copy the lexeme buffer,
                         set offsets 16/24/32 (value_int, is_integer,
                         lexeme), advance, return.
  TRUE/FALSE/NULL     -> create the matching node, advance, return.
  TOKEN_ERROR         -> "Lexer error" -> 0.
  Anything else       -> "Unexpected token" -> 0.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Treats `parser` as a trusted parser pointer. Source text is untrusted;
all length-bounded copies use the lexer's length field for slicing so a
hostile literal cannot induce overread.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_value" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse JSON value (entry point for recursive descent)

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current_token is equal to 0:
        proc set_parser_error with parser, "Unexpected end of input"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 32

    Note: Object
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_object from parser
    End If

    Note: Array
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_array from parser
    End If

    Note: String
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 8
        Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 16

        Let node be proc create_json_node with JSON_STRING, line, column

        If node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parser_error with parser, "Out of memory"
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Copy string value
        Let str_copy be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with str_copy, 0, lexeme, 0, lexeme_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with str_copy, lexeme_length, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, str_copy

        proc advance_parser from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Number
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        Let is_int be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 56
        Let value_int be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 40
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 8
        Set lexeme_length to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 16

        Set node to proc create_json_node with JSON_NUMBER, line, column

        If node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parser_error with parser, "Out of memory"
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Copy lexeme for float parsing
        Let lexeme_copy be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with lexeme_copy, 0, lexeme, 0, lexeme_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with lexeme_copy, lexeme_length, 0

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value_int
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, is_int
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, lexeme_copy

        proc advance_parser from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: true
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TRUE from Lexer:
        Set node to proc create_json_node with JSON_TRUE, line, column
        proc advance_parser from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: false
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FALSE from Lexer:
        Set node to proc create_json_node with JSON_FALSE, line, column
        proc advance_parser from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: null
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NULL from Lexer:
        Set node to proc create_json_node with JSON_NULL, line, column
        proc advance_parser from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Error
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ERROR from Lexer:
        proc set_parser_error with parser, "Lexer error"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc set_parser_error with parser, "Unexpected token"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Implements the object production:
  object  ::= "{" members "}"
  members ::= pair ("," pair)* | epsilon
  pair    ::= string ":" value
The keys list and the children list are kept parallel (keys[i] pairs
with children[i]) so that downstream translators can iterate by index
rather than maintaining a separate name -> value map; the parallel-
list arrangement also preserves source order, which is required by the
JSON spec's "members are ordered" interpretation that downstream
tooling relies on.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Capture starting line/column from the current token. Consume `{` via
expect_token; on failure return 0. Create the JSON_OBJECT node; on OOM
report error and return 0. Allocate two backing Lists (keys, children)
via List.create; on either OOM, set error and return 0 (destroying the
first list if it succeeded). Bind them into the node's offsets 40/48.
If the next token is `}`, advance and return the empty object. Otherwise
loop:
  - require a STRING key; on miss, set "Expected string key in object"
    and return 0;
  - copy the key bytes to a heap NUL-terminated buffer and advance;
  - require `:` via expect_token;
  - recurse via parse_value to obtain value_node; propagate failure;
  - List.append the key to keys and the value to children;
  - if next is `,`, advance and continue; otherwise break.
After the loop, consume `}` via expect_token. Returns the populated
JSON_OBJECT node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_object" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse JSON object

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 32

    Note: Expect '{'
    Let result1 be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer, "Expected '{'"

    If result1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node be proc create_json_node with JSON_OBJECT, line, column

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parser_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create children and keys lists
    Let children be proc create from List
    Let keys be proc create from List

    If children is equal to 0:
        proc set_parser_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    If keys is equal to 0:
        proc destroy from List with children
        proc set_parser_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, keys

    Note: Check for empty object
    Let is_close_brace be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer

    If is_close_brace is equal to 1:
        proc advance_parser from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Parse members
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Parse key (must be string)
        Let is_string be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_STRING from Lexer

        If is_string is equal to 0:
            proc set_parser_error with parser, "Expected string key in object"
            Return 0
        End If

        Let key_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let key_lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with key_token, 8
        Let key_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with key_token, 16

        Note: Copy key
        Let key_copy be proc allocate from Layout with key_length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with key_copy, 0, key_lexeme, 0, key_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with key_copy, key_length, 0

        proc advance_parser from parser

        Note: Expect ':'
        Let result2 be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer, "Expected ':' after key"

        If result2 is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Parse value
        Let value_node be proc parse_value from parser

        If value_node is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Add key and value
        proc append from List with keys, key_copy
        proc append from List with children, value_node

        Note: Check for comma or end
        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_parser from parser
            Note: Continue to next pair
        Otherwise:
            Note: Must be closing brace
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Expect '}'
    Let result3 be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer, "Expected '}'"

    If result3 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Implements the array production:
  array    ::= "[" elements "]"
  elements ::= value ("," value)* | epsilon
The children list preserves source order. No keys list is allocated
since arrays are positional.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Capture starting line/column. Consume `[` via expect_token. Create the
JSON_ARRAY node; on OOM report error and return 0. Allocate the children
List via List.create; on OOM report error and return 0. Bind it at
offset 40 of the node. If the next token is `]`, advance and return the
empty array. Otherwise loop:
  - recurse via parse_value to obtain value_node; propagate failure;
  - List.append value_node to children;
  - if next is `,`, advance and continue; otherwise break.
After the loop, consume `]` via expect_token. Returns the populated
JSON_ARRAY node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_array" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse JSON array

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 32

    Note: Expect '['
    Let result1 be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected '['"

    If result1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node be proc create_json_node with JSON_ARRAY, line, column

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parser_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create children list
    Let children be proc create from List

    If children is equal to 0:
        proc set_parser_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, children

    Note: Check for empty array
    Let is_close_bracket be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer

    If is_close_bracket is equal to 1:
        proc advance_parser from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Parse elements
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Parse value
        Let value_node be proc parse_value from parser

        If value_node is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Add value
        proc append from List with children, value_node

        Note: Check for comma or end
        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_parser from parser
            Note: Continue to next element
        Otherwise:
            Note: Must be closing bracket
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Expect ']'
    Let result2 be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected ']'"

    If result2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Parse Function
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The single public entry point. Owns the full lifetime of the lexer and
parser so callers only deal with the AST. The trailing-content check
after parse_value catches a class of bug where a document is technically
parseable but the user actually concatenated two documents -- e.g.,
"{}{}" -- which the spec considers invalid. By failing on trailing
content we surface that to the user immediately rather than silently
discarding the second document.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guard source!=0. Create a Lexer via Lexer.create_json_lexer; on failure
return 0. Create a parser via create_json_parser; on failure destroy the
lexer and return 0. Call parse_value to obtain ast_root. If non-zero,
inspect parser's current_token (offset 8) and its token_type (token
offset 0): if not TOKEN_EOF, call set_parser_error with "Unexpected
content after JSON value" and set ast_root to 0. Destroy parser, destroy
lexer, return ast_root.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
`source` is treated as untrusted input. All bounds-checking is done by
the lexer; this driver doesn't inspect the bytes directly. Resource
cleanup is always run, even on parse failure, so a malformed input
cannot leak the lexer or parser blocks.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_json" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse JSON source string and return AST root

    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create lexer
    Let lexer be proc create_json_lexer from Lexer with source

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create parser
    Let parser be proc create_json_parser from lexer

    If parser is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_json_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse value
    Let ast_root be proc parse_value from parser

    Note: Check for trailing content
    If ast_root is not equal to 0:
        Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

        If current_token is not equal to 0:
            Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 0

            If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Note: Unexpected content after JSON value
                proc set_parser_error with parser, "Unexpected content after JSON value"
                Set ast_root to 0
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Cleanup
    proc destroy_json_parser from parser
    proc destroy_json_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    Return ast_root
End Process

Note: End of JSON Parser
